			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Deep priority conflicts in the wild: a pilot study</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LuísEduardodeSouzaAmorim.html">Luís Eduardo de Souza Amorim</a>, <a href="../profile/MichaelJSteindorfer.html">Michael J. Steindorfer</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136020">10.1145/3136014.3136020</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> It is a pilot study of deep priority conflicts found in real-world grammars.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The subject matter is analysis of grammar specifications to identify and characterize conflicts.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Such conflicts motivate grammar refactoring and long-term maintenance of language definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The analyzed artifacts are context-free grammars, i.e., meta-language descriptions of syntax.
</li></ul></li></ul>
